The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Panel to resist ban
                                                                                                               Panel to resist ban
          A STAFF REPORTER                              
	Transport operators on Tuesday formed an umbrella body called the Banijyik Paribahan Bachao Committee to resist the implementation of the high court ban on two-stroke autos and commercial vehicles over 15 years old. The committee will also fight government atrocities against transporters.        
	All bus, minibus, taxi and auto unions have come together under the banner, cutting across party lines, claimed committee members.         
	The transporters plan to move the Supreme Court, seeking a stay on the ban.        
	Hospital supplies: Naresh Rajak, 48, was arrested in his Sealdah home on Tuesday for hoarding medical and surgical equipment meant for government hospitals. The goods, worth lakhs, were sold to him by employees of government hospitals, said police.        
	Genomics centre: The proposed genomics institute in Kalyani will start functioning by September and become fully operational in a couple of years, the state government announced on Tuesday. Construction of the National Institute of Biomedical Genomics, funded by the Centre, has started on a 30-acre plot donated by the state government.        
	The institute is expected to launch Indias first large-scale programme for screening newborns for genetic disorders and spearhead the countrys efforts in the global cancer genome consortium. Research work will start at the genomics institute by September. The centre will be linked through satellite with the medical colleges in the state, said Bengal health minister Surjya Kanta Mishra at Swastha Bhavan on Tuesday.        
	Truck racket: Calcutta police have claimed to have busted an inter-state heavy vehicle theft racket after arresting three key members  Ramakant Shaw from Baranagar and Surendra Shaw from Daulatpur and Anil Yadav from Jamuni in Bihar  last week. The racket had links in Uttar Pradesh and Andhra Pradesh.                                                                                                                                                                           
